'''''Myths to Live By''''' is a 1972 book, a collection of essays, originally given as lectures at the [[Cooper Union]] Forum, by [[mythologist]] [[Joseph Campbell]] between 1958 and 1971. The work has an introduction by Johnson E. Fairchild.

The deep power of [[mythology|myth]] on the inner, spiritual lives of human beings throughout the ages (including our own age) is the common theme running throughout all of the essays in the collection. Campbell explains the differences between western and oriental myths and rites. He shows how fundamental universal thoughts are adapted to local requirements of legitimation. A typical form of adaptation of the ''hero'' is the American image of the ''lone rider'' who dispels evil.<ref>Edition London 1985, p. 193.</ref>  

